I often think, the millennium generation may be the last one that can purely appreciate art and establish a connection with artists. They don't have that kind of pressure, and they don't have to wear a critical, colored lens to view everything.
We grew up in the golden age of media, at a time when people had a common understanding of popular culture, but now that collective consciousness has disappeared.
Back then, we didn't have to consider the source of the content, and we could directly immerse ourselves in it, because in that era, tracing the roots was not an easy thing to do.
We revered these artists as deities, and there was no reason to question this worship. As a result, we established a kind of "pseudo-social relationship" with them, and considered it an indispensable part of life.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
We used to gather with our friends every Thursday while watching the drama "The Office" when it was on the air.
This experience is vastly different from how we watch TV shows on streaming platforms nowadays.
Deep down, we all yearn for that collective sense of belonging that brings everyone together.
It's precisely because of our nostalgia that we keep rewatching dramas like "The Office" and movies like "The King's Speech" that have those unforgettable catchphrases that spread like memes online.
We reference these catchphrases from the works and assume most people understand them.
Even if some things go viral online now, we can't assume everyone has seen them.
With the explosion of information, there's just too much we need to pay attention to – and we can't even narrow it down... Do we still have a chance to get out of this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find that they either have a history of scandals or are full of prejudice – and it's all just a vicious cycle that gets exhausting.
We're torn between nostalgia and the fact that the creators of the art we love may have had serious moral flaws – this inner conflict leaves us feeling at a loss.
We'll be even more careful about establishing "social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realize that in order to acquire wealth and power, it's difficult to ensure that we won't harm others or take advantage of others.
Due to the disappearance of media collective consciousness, we have formed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are also some people who are still stubbornly unaware, insisting on putting others on a pedestal, and pretending to be shocked by the collapse of the idol.
We are in a period of transformation, and I am eager to know where we will go from here.
